properties.title: Chichester
properties.E159_alternative_house: Recommendation to build a Custom House at Dell Quay in the parish of Apuldram, on land held of the Queen by Humphrey Ryman; and the merchants resorting thither will be much more eased, and the Queen's Majesty not be very greatly charged, because there are certain old walls of that same decayed, which may serve towards the making of the said Custom House.
properties.E159_notes: More frequented and haunted with merchants and merchandises than in times pastï¿½ more than any in Sussex except Rye. Of such breadth and depth that therein may harbour 500 great ships, without danger of weather or enemies. The bar, that before the putting down of the weirs was wont to annoy the ships there resorting, is so much abated within four years last past, as at the low water mark there the water is deeper than before, five feet, so that a ship of 100 tons may safely come over that bar without danage at three-quarter flood. From the bar to Itchenor is three miles, and from thence a barque of 40 tons may come into the Dell, being the quay of the port. In the said port or haven of Chichester there are four places where merchandize and goods be taken in and discharged, viz. Crakewode, West-deepe, Longwater, and in a place towards Thorney, which places have been so used time out of mind, but it is not mete they should be continued, but that all goods coming into the port of Chichester should be unladen at Dell Quay. The Customer of the port of Chichester hath dwelled at Rye, and appointed a deputy. properties.title: Harwich Haven
properties.E159_notes: We think it very mete & expedient for the good service of the Prince to have a storehouse at Harwich & the Customer  to have a deputy always resident there because that the said town of Harwich standeth at the mouth of the water that taketh his course to Ipswich and is of ancient time called Orwell Haven, which is of such depth before the town of Harwich as any ship may come in and out at a low water, & diverse and sundry times the ships and other vessels of foreign parties are driven to lie before the said town, sometimes for extremity of weather, sometimes of nexessity of victuals, and many times to make sale of such wares & merchandises as they have in freight; And because that there is neither the Customer nor his deputy resident in the said town of Harwich and there ships many times being of such burthen as they are not able to pass to Ipswich by the deacy of the haven, And yet if they were they must observe the tides which require sometimes a longer abode than they are able to suffer they are compelled to depart without making sale of any their said ware & merchandises to the great hindrance of the Queen's Majestry of her Custom and loss and prejudice to the country. And yet we think it not mete that the said storehouse at Harwich should receive or discharge any ware or merchandises but in such cases of necessity, and that for the causes ensuing: One is if it were understand to the enemy that the whole traffic of charging and discharging were at that place and that the whole substance and wealth of ware & merchandises aswell inward as outward remained there from time to time, & knowing that they might come in and out at all times at their pleasure, the town also lying in such an Andle, and so environed with water as there is no passage to the same by land but at one street so that if the enemies should approach they might easily enter, spoil, and fire the town before the country could come to the rescue thereof, unless the Prince should defend it continually with a garrison of men, which were more charge than gain; The other is it will be an utter decay to the Queen's Majesty's town and port of Ipswich and to the whole country adjoining a great trouble & unquietness of the rest of the country which now have their wares & merchandises discharged 7 or 8 miles within the land and then should be driven to make their carriage so much further from their ancient trade & dwelling places. Also, there is a house claimed to be the Duke's Grace's of Norfolk holden of her Majesty as of her manor there by the rent of 8d per annum which house will be very apt & commodious for that service, & is in much ruin & decay, the reparations whereof will cost by estimation ï¿½20, but what the charges of the purchase thereof will be we know not.

properties.title: Ipswich
properties.E159_repairable: Partly decayed and not so much frequented as heretofore it hath been, and so hath continued by the space of 20 years last past, the occasion thereof been diverse. First no great ship or vessel above the burden of 40, 50, or 60 tons came or may come any further upwards towards the port of Ipswich than Downham Bridge, where may ride a vessel of 100 tons. Also, the said stream is partly landed up by certain mills erected at Ipswich Town End, and so upwards to the head of this stream where, as we are informed, the salt water hath had his course at a full sea into the main land three miles, and hath repulsed the fresh water casuing it to swell six miles above Ipswich; and now the salt water is so strengthened by the said mill dams that it is stopped at Ipswich so that the said salt water at the flood can not have his full course up the river, as before the erecting of those mills it was accustomed thereby giving the fresh water such head & repulse as at the low ebb the violence thereof cannot drive & scour down all such sand, ooze, and other silt as the sea commonly at every flowing water bringeth up as in time past. Also all the rubbish, filth, and baggage of the whole town of Ipswish is not weekly carried by cart into the fields (as in London) and other well-ordered towns, but thrown into the streets & back lanes, & with every rain water washed into the haven, by which means the channel of the said stream lying as it doth even crookedly as an eel, is of late years very much impaired, which things as well for the better maintenance of the port as of that town is very needfull and requisite to be reformed & amended, the costs & charges whereof by estimation will amount to the sum of 1000 marks.
properties.E159_inheritance: There is a Custom House belonging to the said port at the west end of the common warehouse of the said town, beneath under a loft, parcel & belonging to the said warehouse, which Custom House containeth in length 20 feet and in breadth 14 feet, and standeth directly over against the quay of that port, having a certain open gallery or walking place before the same of 9 feet wide, standing upon posts with rails for men to lean upon, and is sufficiently well-repaired at the charges of the bailiffs of the same town and so is to be continued. The rent thereof is by year to the bailiff and burgesses of the said town 20 shillings; and the residue of that storehouse contains in length 90 feet in breadth 20 feet.
properties.E159_alternative_house: At Ipswich is a house more apt & commodious to be purchased of one Raynbow for a Custom House there for the better oversight of Her Majesty, the inheritance where of will cost [blank].
properties.E159_notes: It is manifest unto us by examination and view of the creeks & places aforesaid [under the supervision of Ipswich] that ware and merchandises have been of late time & some of long continuance used to be taken in & discharged at many of the forenamed creeks & lading places, but for the better service of the Prince & benefit of the Country, we think them not mete so to be continued or suffered, but rather to be all damned & disallowed (Except Ipswich, Harwich, Colchester Hithe, Maldon, Brightlingsea, & Leigh), because at all the other places commonly wares, merchandises, victuals, and all other commodities of this Realm specially from & out of the countries adjoining Corn & victuals, merchandises & others have been and daily be transported into the parties of beyond the Seas & to all other ports & creeks within this Realm at all men's pleasures without the knowledge or consent of the Customers, Controllers, or Searcher, as well to the deceit of the Prince as also to the great lack and discommodity of the said country adjoining. properties.title: Kings Lynn
properties.E159_repairable:
The allegation of the mayor and other the inhabitants of the port town of Lynn, how and by what occasion the said port is decayed.
Imprimis they allege that in time past there was used much clothing in the said port town of clothes called Lynn Whitts, whereof the most part were conveyed on the seas as well by the inhabitants there as by merchants strangers who came for the same and brought in other merchandise the which clothing hath been of long time decayed by reason of the great mass of unwrought wools carried over by the Staplers, so as in the parts beyond the seas they practised there the making of such cloths themselves whereby the vent of the said Whitts decayed and aswell the people that were set on work thereby as the merchants trade of occupying the same did soon decay & diminish, and consequently the town fell to great ruin. And the wonted repair of merchant strangers is lately withdrawn by whom the town did utter great plenty of corn, which is one of the principallest merchandises of this port beside the said cloths.
They further allege that in time past they had free liberty to traffic with their cloths and other merchandise unto Flanders & the Low Countries without any impeachment, whereof now they be inhibited by reason of the Company of the Merchant Venturers who restraineth all men except such as be of the said company, or at least all other be driven to seek such corners & live in such fear of their straight orders as few have pleasure to traffic of the seas.
They also allege that the inhabitants of the said port in time past had great traffic into Iceland to their great benefit, the which they be now also inhibited by reason of the King of Denmark will not permit them neither to buy nor sell as at that time they did.
properties.E159_inheritance: The Custom House belongs to the town, and is lent to the Crown officers without rent. It serves the purpose reasonably well. There is cost to be done to make the passage new up into it, glazing, and the gutters, costing no more than ï¿½20. The mayor and brethren are contented that Her Highness shall have it for ever by such assurance as her Majesty's Council can devise for 4 shillings of yearly rent & bearing the reparations, reserving to themselves the lower part which is the Condytt House of the said town.
properties.E159_notes: Decayed and not so well frequented & haunted as it hath been in times past, but yet much better frequented than any of the rest of the creeks be. Other decayed creeks there be which we speak not of becasue we see no necessity to repair them. The west side of the town of Lynn is builded upon the waters side and all their warehouses & storehouses be opened upon the same so that they may receive & deliver wares & merchandises in & out of the same warehouses to the fraud of the Queen's Majesty if great attendance be not given by her Highness's officers; and as to any of the said creeks we find no such place of suspicion.

properties.title: Yarmouth,  Great
properties.E159_repairable: Decayed 50 years ago by the death of a great number of inhabitants including merchants, following which the peir and other defences were not maintained. The mouth of the haven has been stopped by the violence of the sea casting in sand and gravel, causing ships to unload in the Thames or at sea; merchants are forced to send their wares to Norwich by carts . The decay is evident in the large ancient buidlings at Norwich, some of which are decayed and unoccupied. Inhabitants of Yarmouth used to be occupied in the Iceland fishing trade, and finding coastal trade subject to 'great charges & discouragement' they seek to live on the land by farming, handicrafts or other occupations. Nevertheless, great sums have already been spent on trying to mend the haven. Repair is very necessary, but no estimate of the cost can be made; the 'chief defence thereof is to be made by 2 great peirs in to the main Sea which is to be considered only by discrete and expert workmen'.
properties.E159_inheritance: The Customer uses his own house.
